1
00:00:13,849 --> 00:00:16,455
[###]

2
00:01:42,145 --> 00:01:44,752
[###]

3
00:02:16,596 --> 00:02:19,203
[SPEAKS IN LATIN]

4
00:02:31,278 --> 00:02:33,884
[PRAYING QUIETLY]

5
00:02:40,704 --> 00:02:43,310
[PRAYING QUIETLY]

6
00:02:51,256 --> 00:02:53,877
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

7
00:02:54,092 --> 00:02:56,699
Sir Thomas.
Your Grace.

8
00:03:02,851 --> 00:03:04,351
MAN 1 : Your Grace.
MAN 2: Sir Thomas.

9
00:03:04,352 --> 00:03:08,105
MORE:
Ambassador Chapuys,
I thought you had abandoned us.

10
00:03:08,106 --> 00:03:12,851
Ha-ha. It's true. I did. Or tried to.

11
00:03:13,278 --> 00:03:16,322
In all conscience,
I could never abandon Her Majesty.

12
00:03:16,323 --> 00:03:19,450
She is the most gracious
and wonderful woman in the world.

13
00:03:19,451 --> 00:03:22,036
And the saddest.
I agree with you.

14
00:03:22,037 --> 00:03:24,079
So does the emperor.

15
00:03:24,080 --> 00:03:26,457
He has written this letter
of encouragement,

16
00:03:26,458 --> 00:03:30,597
and support for your efforts
on her behalf.

17
00:03:31,880 --> 00:03:35,237
I beg you not to deliver it to me.

18
00:03:35,342 --> 00:03:38,594
Although I have given
more than sufficient proof
of my loyalty to the king,

19
00:03:38,595 --> 00:03:40,804
I must do nothing
to provoke suspicion.

20
00:03:40,805 --> 00:03:43,673
Consider the times we live in.

21
00:03:44,184 --> 00:03:45,768
I don't want to be deprived

22
00:03:45,769 --> 00:03:49,480
of the liberty which allows me
to speak boldly in private

23
00:03:49,481 --> 00:03:53,192
about those matters which concern
your master and the queen.

24
00:03:53,193 --> 00:03:56,644
I understand.
You need say no more.

25
00:03:59,157 --> 00:04:02,775
Thank you, Mr. Cromwell.
Your Majesty.

26
00:04:03,370 --> 00:04:05,871
SERVANT:
Sir Thomas More.

27
00:04:05,872 --> 00:04:08,479
Cromwell.

28
00:04:09,876 --> 00:04:12,044
Sir Thomas.

29
00:04:12,045 --> 00:04:13,671
Your Majesty.

30
00:04:13,672 --> 00:04:16,006
I must tell you,
I have received a petition

31
00:04:16,007 --> 00:04:18,342
from the members
of the House of Commons.

32
00:04:18,343 --> 00:04:24,223
Complaining of the cruel
behaviour and abuses
of the prelates and the clergy.

33
00:04:24,224 --> 00:04:26,642
Thomas,

34
00:04:26,643 --> 00:04:30,979
people are asking for freedom
from clerical rule.

35
00:04:30,981 --> 00:04:33,023
Your Majesty knows very well

36
00:04:33,024 --> 00:04:35,984
that I have always condemned
the abuses of the clergy

37
00:04:35,986 --> 00:04:39,029
when they have been brought
to light. As your chancellor,

38
00:04:39,030 --> 00:04:44,410
I have worked hard to eliminate them
and purify our Holy Church.

39
00:04:44,411 --> 00:04:47,017
But...

40
00:04:47,372 --> 00:04:48,997
You know where I stand.

41
00:04:48,999 --> 00:04:50,207
[SCOFFS]

42
00:04:50,208 --> 00:04:52,751
You've always known.

43
00:04:52,752 --> 00:04:56,702
I cannot condone
this newfangled vision

44
00:04:56,923 --> 00:04:59,508
of private belief
and personal grace.

45
00:04:59,509 --> 00:05:04,805
For me, the Church is the permanent
and living sign of God's presence.

46
00:05:04,806 --> 00:05:09,764
It is a visible, palpable community.

47
00:05:11,896 --> 00:05:15,315
Not just a few brethren
gathered in secret rooms.

48
00:05:15,316 --> 00:05:17,923
[###]

49
00:05:20,238 --> 00:05:23,189
Then you will speak against me?

50
00:05:25,452 --> 00:05:28,412
My loyalty and love
for Your Majesty is so great

51
00:05:28,413 --> 00:05:33,376
that I will never say a word
against you in public.

52
00:05:34,919 --> 00:05:37,526
So help me God.

53
00:05:41,551 --> 00:05:44,158
[DOOR CLOSES]

54
00:05:45,930 --> 00:05:47,931
[PEOPLE ARGUlNG]

55
00:05:47,932 --> 00:05:50,539
[CANE BANGlNG ON FLOOR]

56
00:05:50,602 --> 00:05:53,209
All rise for the king!

57
00:05:55,774 --> 00:05:57,608
MAN 1 : Your Majesty.
MAN 2: Your Majesty.

58
00:05:57,609 --> 00:06:00,110
MAN 3: Your Majesty.
MAN 4: Your Majesty.

59
00:06:00,111 --> 00:06:01,737
MAN 5: Your Majesty.
MAN 6: Your Majesty.

60
00:06:01,738 --> 00:06:04,345
[BELL TOLLlNG]

61
00:06:09,120 --> 00:06:12,038
HENRY:
My Lords, Your Graces,

62
00:06:12,248 --> 00:06:14,625
we have come here among you
to hear your response

63
00:06:14,626 --> 00:06:17,586
to the charges and responsibilities
laid against you.

64
00:06:17,587 --> 00:06:19,963
You are generally charged
with supporting the authority

65
00:06:19,964 --> 00:06:22,007
of the late Cardinal Wolsey,

66
00:06:22,008 --> 00:06:26,303
and the bishop of Rome, against
that of your own king and country.

67
00:06:26,304 --> 00:06:28,911
[CROWD CHATTERlNG]

68
00:06:30,517 --> 00:06:36,012
Some here among you may suppose
I seek personal advantage.

69
00:06:36,147 --> 00:06:38,273
It is not so.

70
00:06:38,274 --> 00:06:40,317
As your king,

71
00:06:40,318 --> 00:06:43,612
I am commissioned
to restore right order on Earth

72
00:06:43,613 --> 00:06:45,239
and assert the immunities

73
00:06:45,240 --> 00:06:49,326
and princely liberties
of our realm and crown.

74
00:06:49,327 --> 00:06:51,934
[CROWD CHATTERlNG]

75
00:06:52,247 --> 00:06:54,998
This is my sacred duty,

76
00:06:56,334 --> 00:06:59,121
sealed before God,

77
00:06:59,921 --> 00:07:03,788
and by solemn oath
at my coronation.

78
00:07:04,134 --> 00:07:06,301
[MAN CLEARS THROAT]

79
00:07:06,302 --> 00:07:10,338
What is your conclusion,
Archbishop Warham?

80
00:07:10,723 --> 00:07:15,644
Your Majesty, before I deliver it,
I give way to His Grace,

81
00:07:15,645 --> 00:07:19,147
the most Reverent Bishop Fisher,
the Bishop of Rochester.

82
00:07:19,149 --> 00:07:21,755
[CROWD MURMURlNG]

83
00:07:28,032 --> 00:07:30,639
My Lords,

84
00:07:31,119 --> 00:07:33,787
we are asked
to admit His Majesty,

85
00:07:33,788 --> 00:07:37,761
as supreme head
of the Church in England.

86
00:07:38,251 --> 00:07:41,336
Unfortunately,
we cannot grant this to the king,

87
00:07:41,337 --> 00:07:45,465
without abandoning our unity
with the see of Rome.

88
00:07:45,466 --> 00:07:47,885
[CROWD CHATTERlNG]

89
00:07:47,886 --> 00:07:52,014
If we are to renounce the unity
of the Christian world

90
00:07:52,015 --> 00:07:55,384
and leap out of Peter's ship,

91
00:07:55,602 --> 00:07:58,729
then we shall be drowned
in the waves of all heresies,

92
00:07:58,730 --> 00:08:01,273
sects, schisms and divisions.

93
00:08:01,274 --> 00:08:02,983
[CROWD DlSAGREElNG]

94
00:08:02,984 --> 00:08:05,027
I say to you,

95
00:08:05,028 --> 00:08:09,239
that the acceptance of regal
supremacy over our Holy Church,

96
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:15,742
would represent a tearing asunder
of the seamless coat of Christ.

97
00:08:15,955 --> 00:08:17,956
[CROWD CHATTERlNG]

98
00:08:17,957 --> 00:08:20,292
[CANE BANGS TWlCE ON FLOOR]

99
00:08:20,293 --> 00:08:22,586
CHAMBERLAlN:
Your Grace,

100
00:08:22,587 --> 00:08:25,235
we will hear your judgement.

101
00:08:25,506 --> 00:08:29,753
I will put this proposal
to convocation,

102
00:08:29,969 --> 00:08:33,223
that Your Majesty has a new title:

103
00:08:33,932 --> 00:08:37,726
Supreme head of the Church
and clergy of England.

104
00:08:37,727 --> 00:08:39,478
[CROWD MURMURlNG]

105
00:08:39,479 --> 00:08:42,086
But I add the caveat:

106
00:08:42,357 --> 00:08:46,437
"As far as the law of Christ allows."

107
00:08:46,778 --> 00:08:48,487
[CROWD MURMURlNG]

108
00:08:48,488 --> 00:08:51,095
MAN:
A trick.

109
00:08:51,824 --> 00:08:53,408
WARHAM:
Those in favour?

110
00:08:53,409 --> 00:08:56,016
[###]

111
00:09:08,925 --> 00:09:10,968
WARHAM:
Very well.

112
00:09:10,969 --> 00:09:14,005
[SPEAKS lN LATlN]

113
00:09:14,430 --> 00:09:19,258
Whoever remains silent
shall be assumed to agree.

114
00:09:24,816 --> 00:09:28,267
Thank you, Your Grace.

115
00:09:48,298 --> 00:09:50,215
[BELL TOLLlNG]

116
00:09:50,216 --> 00:09:52,823
[MAN SPEAKlNG lN LATlN]

117
00:10:08,610 --> 00:10:11,216
[CROWD RESPONDS]

118
00:10:12,530 --> 00:10:15,733
Cardinal Campeggio.
Holy Father.

119
00:10:18,202 --> 00:10:23,957
Sit down, Cardinal Campeggio.
I know you are a martyr to gout.

120
00:10:23,958 --> 00:10:27,347
Ah. And my feet are killing me too.

121
00:10:27,545 --> 00:10:29,379
What do you want to see me about?

122
00:10:29,380 --> 00:10:31,465
We have received two new letters

123
00:10:31,466 --> 00:10:33,842
regarding the King of England's
great matter.

124
00:10:33,843 --> 00:10:37,010
Oh, that again.

125
00:10:37,430 --> 00:10:39,473
What do they say?

126
00:10:39,474 --> 00:10:41,808
Well, the first
is from the king himself,

127
00:10:41,809 --> 00:10:46,229
urging the curia to make a final and
favourable decision on his annulment,

128
00:10:46,230 --> 00:10:49,400
for the sake of peace in England.

129
00:10:49,901 --> 00:10:54,237
He uses some intemperate language,
Holiness, complaining that:

130
00:10:54,238 --> 00:10:57,783
"Never was there any prince handled
by a pope

131
00:10:57,784 --> 00:11:00,660
as Your Holiness has treated us."

132
00:11:00,661 --> 00:11:04,498
He meant my predecessor and,
frankly, he has a point.

133
00:11:04,499 --> 00:11:07,459
Clement
was a terrible procrastinator.

134
00:11:07,460 --> 00:11:11,254
Although it was very wrong for some
people to dig up his dead body

135
00:11:11,255 --> 00:11:15,175
and stab it in the street,
I can well understand their feelings.

136
00:11:15,176 --> 00:11:16,635
He was never popular.

137
00:11:16,636 --> 00:11:19,054
[SPEAKS lN LATlN]

138
00:11:19,055 --> 00:11:20,764
And the second letter?

139
00:11:20,765 --> 00:11:22,182
From the emperor.

140
00:11:22,183 --> 00:11:26,186
On behalf of his aunt, Catherine,
the unhappy queen,

141
00:11:26,187 --> 00:11:30,054
urging you
to prevent the annulment

142
00:11:30,274 --> 00:11:33,441
and excommunicate the king.

143
00:11:34,529 --> 00:11:38,387
It is true we must come
to a judgement.

144
00:11:39,701 --> 00:11:42,307
On the other hand,

145
00:11:42,704 --> 00:11:44,871
to protect the interests
of the Church,

146
00:11:44,872 --> 00:11:48,542
we should try not to antagonize
one power above the other.

147
00:11:48,543 --> 00:11:51,169
After all,
they have soldiers and guns,

148
00:11:51,170 --> 00:11:55,612
whereas we must make do
with beauty and truth.

149
00:11:56,509 --> 00:11:59,886
What of this girl, this putain,
the king's whore?

150
00:11:59,887 --> 00:12:01,805
Anne Boleyn.
Yes.

151
00:12:01,806 --> 00:12:04,307
Why doesn't someone
just get rid of her?

152
00:12:04,308 --> 00:12:06,915
[###]

153
00:12:23,661 --> 00:12:25,662
No.

154
00:12:25,663 --> 00:12:28,270
Don't get up.

155
00:12:32,879 --> 00:12:35,485
Stay like that.

156
00:12:39,093 --> 00:12:41,700
You're so very beautiful.

157
00:12:42,638 --> 00:12:45,245
So very desirable.

158
00:12:47,727 --> 00:12:50,728
I have to possess you utterly.

159
00:12:59,781 --> 00:13:01,531
I can't wait.

160
00:13:01,532 --> 00:13:04,139
Oh, my love,

161
00:13:04,327 --> 00:13:08,953
just a little longer. And then...

162
00:13:12,710 --> 00:13:16,652
I am made head of the Church
of England.

163
00:13:17,798 --> 00:13:20,405
Is it true?

164
00:13:20,468 --> 00:13:22,469
[CHUCKLES]

165
00:13:22,470 --> 00:13:26,254
Then I am so glad.

166
00:13:26,641 --> 00:13:29,891
At last you have your right,

167
00:13:30,353 --> 00:13:32,959
and can do as you will.

168
00:13:35,525 --> 00:13:40,320
I'm going to have Cromwell refurbish
some of the apartments in the Tower.

169
00:13:40,321 --> 00:13:45,861
Every Queen of England stays there
before her coronation.

170
00:13:58,673 --> 00:14:01,279
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

171
00:14:04,095 --> 00:14:06,304
Papa.

172
00:14:06,305 --> 00:14:08,390
What's wrong?

173
00:14:08,391 --> 00:14:10,350
Don't you want to celebrate?

174
00:14:10,351 --> 00:14:12,227
It's far too early for that.

175
00:14:12,228 --> 00:14:15,763
The bishops
were not really defeated.

176
00:14:16,190 --> 00:14:19,526
By default, they voted to make
the king head of the Church,

177
00:14:19,527 --> 00:14:23,854
but only as far
as the law of Christ allows.

178
00:14:24,115 --> 00:14:27,200
You don't have to be a clever lawyer
to know that the law of Christ

179
00:14:27,201 --> 00:14:29,953
may be used to invalidate
the vote itself.

180
00:14:29,954 --> 00:14:32,655
Then it was all for nothing.

181
00:14:33,833 --> 00:14:35,917
No.

182
00:14:35,918 --> 00:14:38,525
Not for nothing.

183
00:14:38,588 --> 00:14:42,299
The principle has now been
effectively conceded
by most of them.

184
00:14:42,300 --> 00:14:45,510
As George told me, their resistance
and recalcitrance

185
00:14:45,511 --> 00:14:48,382
really stem from only one man.

186
00:14:48,723 --> 00:14:51,955
That bloody Bishop Fisher.
Fisher.

187
00:14:54,770 --> 00:14:57,188
[MEN LAUGHlNG, CHATTERlNG]

188
00:14:57,189 --> 00:14:59,816
SERVANT: Sir.
Ah. Mr. Cranmer.

189
00:14:59,817 --> 00:15:02,819
I'm so sorry to be late, Mr. Cromwell.
It's unforgivable.

190
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:05,030
Nonsense.
We haven't yet begun to dine.

191
00:15:05,031 --> 00:15:06,781
It's good to see you.

192
00:15:06,782 --> 00:15:10,922
Mr. Boleyn, Mr. Wyatt,
this is Mr. Cranmer.

193
00:15:11,287 --> 00:15:14,414
Mr. Cranmer.
You're a man of the cloth, I believe?

194
00:15:14,415 --> 00:15:16,666
And are you not a poet, Mr. Wyatt?

195
00:15:16,667 --> 00:15:20,170
That's the least of my sins. You may
take my confession after supper.

196
00:15:20,171 --> 00:15:22,297
I wouldn't if I were you.
It'll turn your hair white.

197
00:15:22,298 --> 00:15:23,506
[CHUCKLES]

198
00:15:23,507 --> 00:15:24,799
We were discussing,
before you arrived,

199
00:15:24,800 --> 00:15:27,510
the progress
of the convocation of bishops

200
00:15:27,511 --> 00:15:30,263
which was called to decide
upon the king's supremacy.

201
00:15:30,264 --> 00:15:33,892
His Majesty has wisely decided
to appoint George Boleyn here,

202
00:15:33,893 --> 00:15:36,019
to negotiate with Their Graces.

203
00:15:36,020 --> 00:15:38,063
I find most of them accommodating.

204
00:15:38,064 --> 00:15:40,565
Of course, there are a few stubborn
exceptions.

205
00:15:40,566 --> 00:15:43,882
Bishop Fisher, I assume?
Naturally.

206
00:15:44,320 --> 00:15:46,321
May I ask who-- Who else?

207
00:15:46,322 --> 00:15:49,168
The archbishop himself, Warham,

208
00:15:49,825 --> 00:15:53,453
after years of being perfectly pliable
has suddenly become
rather intransigent.

209
00:15:53,454 --> 00:15:56,623
That's because he's old, consequently
he's closer to his Maker,

210
00:15:56,624 --> 00:15:58,750
to whom, in due course,
he must explain himself.

211
00:15:58,751 --> 00:16:01,169
Well, I'm sure it will be a simple
matter for him to explain,

212
00:16:01,170 --> 00:16:03,630
how he helped liberate
his Church

213
00:16:03,631 --> 00:16:06,966
from superstition, religious
falsehoods and clerical greed.

214
00:16:06,967 --> 00:16:09,921
[ALL LAUGH]

215
00:16:10,179 --> 00:16:12,786
[###]

216
00:16:44,463 --> 00:16:47,070
MAN:
Mr. Roose.

217
00:16:49,552 --> 00:16:52,011
Yes, sir.

218
00:16:52,012 --> 00:16:54,139
A cook,

219
00:16:54,140 --> 00:16:56,746
by trade.

220
00:16:57,727 --> 00:17:00,333
Yes, sir.

221
00:17:01,063 --> 00:17:04,734
You understand
what's expected of you?

222
00:17:06,652 --> 00:17:09,688
I do. Yes.

223
00:17:11,365 --> 00:17:13,972
This is for your trouble.

224
00:17:22,543 --> 00:17:25,150
If you betray us,

225
00:17:26,088 --> 00:17:30,584
I will destroy your entire family.

226
00:17:44,607 --> 00:17:47,213
[COlNS CLlNKlNG]

227
00:18:23,020 --> 00:18:27,190
Majesty, this is Mr. Cranmer,
of whom I have often spoken.

228
00:18:27,191 --> 00:18:29,567
It was Cranmer
who first spoke to the fact

229
00:18:29,568 --> 00:18:34,197
that your Majesty's great matter was
a theological issue, not a legal one.

230
00:18:34,198 --> 00:18:36,805
Mr. Cranmer.

231
00:18:38,494 --> 00:18:42,622
I have desired to meet you
almost above any person now living.

232
00:18:42,623 --> 00:18:45,708
You are most welcome here at court.

233
00:18:45,709 --> 00:18:47,210
[NERVOUSLY]
M-majesty, l-- l-- Um--

234
00:18:47,211 --> 00:18:51,256
It's funny.
Some of the greatest and most
celebrated minds in my kingdom

235
00:18:51,257 --> 00:18:55,885
sweated and struggled over an issue
which you, an obscure cleric,
if you'll forgive me,

236
00:18:55,886 --> 00:18:59,472
was able to resolve with perfect
simplicity and a clarity of mind,

237
00:18:59,473 --> 00:19:02,260
which put them all to shame.

238
00:19:03,477 --> 00:19:06,084
Majesty, l-- Um--

239
00:19:06,188 --> 00:19:07,647
I--

240
00:19:07,648 --> 00:19:14,582
Mr. Cranmer, His Majesty has decided
to appoint you his personal chaplain.

241
00:19:15,489 --> 00:19:17,282
I--

242
00:19:17,283 --> 00:19:19,784
Uh--

243
00:19:19,785 --> 00:19:22,161
[QUlETLY]
You must thank His Majesty.

244
00:19:22,163 --> 00:19:24,747
Of course.

245
00:19:24,748 --> 00:19:27,355
Majesty.

246
00:19:28,169 --> 00:19:31,370
You are welcome here, Mr. Cranmer.

247
00:19:31,755 --> 00:19:34,591
Mr. Cromwell.
Majesty.

248
00:19:35,342 --> 00:19:37,760
[BELL TOLLlNG]

249
00:19:37,761 --> 00:19:40,680
Well done, Mr. Cranmer, well done.

250
00:19:40,681 --> 00:19:43,288
[DOOR CLOSES]

251
00:19:43,851 --> 00:19:45,643
HENRY:
So you married your ward.

252
00:19:45,644 --> 00:19:48,021
BRANDON: Mm-hm.
HENRY: What's her name?

253
00:19:48,022 --> 00:19:51,482
BRANDON: Catherine Brook.
HENRY: Catherine.

254
00:19:51,483 --> 00:19:53,484
Why her?

255
00:19:53,485 --> 00:19:55,945
I love and admire Miss Brook.

256
00:19:55,946 --> 00:19:58,698
And my young son needs a mother.

257
00:19:58,699 --> 00:20:01,306
How old is she?

258
00:20:01,410 --> 00:20:03,453
Seventeen.

259
00:20:03,454 --> 00:20:06,039
[LAUGHS]

260
00:20:06,040 --> 00:20:08,646
Some mother.

261
00:20:10,044 --> 00:20:12,378
Poor Catherine.

262
00:20:12,379 --> 00:20:16,215
You're incapable of fidelity, Charles.
You always have been.

263
00:20:16,216 --> 00:20:19,835
This time is different.
How different?

264
00:20:22,306 --> 00:20:24,913
I don't know.

265
00:20:25,517 --> 00:20:28,124
I just feel it.

266
00:20:28,395 --> 00:20:32,504
And it's not just
because she's beautiful.

267
00:20:34,068 --> 00:20:36,987
It's a marriage of true souls.

268
00:20:37,988 --> 00:20:40,887
Surely you can understand that.

269
00:20:53,253 --> 00:20:56,539
Oh, sun, go away.

270
00:21:01,428 --> 00:21:04,515
And leave us to our own devices.

271
00:21:05,641 --> 00:21:08,428
[BOTH MOAN]

272
00:21:09,103 --> 00:21:11,771
And I love you, Anne Boleyn.

273
00:21:11,772 --> 00:21:14,379
And I always will.

274
00:21:16,193 --> 00:21:18,800
Always?

275
00:21:19,196 --> 00:21:21,980
How can you say that, Thomas?

276
00:21:22,658 --> 00:21:26,881
Or know what fortune brings
or time changes?

277
00:21:30,457 --> 00:21:33,064
Mm.

278
00:21:33,627 --> 00:21:36,234
Time won't change me.

279
00:21:38,298 --> 00:21:41,465
[BOTH MOAN]

280
00:21:42,761 --> 00:21:45,368
Or this.

281
00:21:47,182 --> 00:21:49,789
[BOTH MOANlNG AND PANTlNG]

282
00:22:07,161 --> 00:22:09,840
ANNE [lN VOlCEOVER]:
Thomas.

283
00:22:13,167 --> 00:22:17,483
[lNSTRUMENTAL MUSlC PLAYlNG,
PEOPLE CHATTERlNG]

284
00:22:18,797 --> 00:22:21,404
My Lady Anne,

285
00:22:21,508 --> 00:22:25,678
you are to be congratulated
for reaching so high.

286
00:22:25,679 --> 00:22:28,014
Thank you, Thomas.

287
00:22:28,015 --> 00:22:31,601
I shall never forget
that we were once true friends.

288
00:22:31,602 --> 00:22:33,144
Oh? Hmm.

289
00:22:33,145 --> 00:22:35,752
I wish I could forget.

290
00:22:35,856 --> 00:22:37,732
But I see you are raised too?

291
00:22:37,733 --> 00:22:38,941
[CHUCKLES]

292
00:22:38,942 --> 00:22:41,194
Only as a sometimes diplomat.

293
00:22:41,195 --> 00:22:43,696
Thanks to the patronage
of Mr. Cromwell, we--

294
00:22:43,697 --> 00:22:46,866
We poets and painters
sometimes have our uses.

295
00:22:46,867 --> 00:22:49,285
There is someone here
I should like you to meet.

296
00:22:49,286 --> 00:22:51,245
Lady Anne Boleyn,
this is Mark Smeaton.

297
00:22:51,246 --> 00:22:55,792
Dancing master, singer, musician,
and, oh, general all-round genius.

298
00:22:55,793 --> 00:22:59,378
Mr. Smeaton.
He likes to be called just plain Mark.

299
00:22:59,379 --> 00:23:01,798
How could he possibly
be called plain?

300
00:23:01,799 --> 00:23:05,084
My Lady. It's a great pleasure.

301
00:23:07,721 --> 00:23:10,453
You play the violin?
Indeed.

302
00:23:10,641 --> 00:23:13,059
Play me something.

303
00:23:13,060 --> 00:23:15,667
Of course.

304
00:23:20,859 --> 00:23:23,466
[PLAYlNG]

305
00:23:54,685 --> 00:23:57,270
[STOPS PLAYlNG]

306
00:23:57,271 --> 00:23:59,877
[APPLAUSE]

307
00:24:02,317 --> 00:24:04,777
Will you show me?

308
00:24:04,778 --> 00:24:07,385
[BELL TOLLlNG]

309
00:24:15,789 --> 00:24:18,396
[PLAYS PLAYFUL TUNE]

310
00:24:23,881 --> 00:24:26,487
[GlGGLES]

311
00:24:28,635 --> 00:24:31,242
[LAUGHTER]

312
00:24:31,388 --> 00:24:33,097
MAN 1 :
There's another guest at the table.

313
00:24:33,098 --> 00:24:34,307
MAN 2:
Who is it?

314
00:24:34,308 --> 00:24:37,476
MAN 1 :
Sir Thomas More is staying.

315
00:24:37,478 --> 00:24:40,084
[DOOR CLOSES]

316
00:25:13,889 --> 00:25:16,891
MORE:
I wanted to thank Your Grace
for your speech to convocation.

317
00:25:16,892 --> 00:25:20,978
It was well said and very brave.
FlSHER: I spoke only truth.

318
00:25:20,979 --> 00:25:25,149
I believe that the caveat "so far
as the law of Christ allows"

319
00:25:25,150 --> 00:25:28,653
does indeed invalidate
the whole bill.

320
00:25:28,654 --> 00:25:34,003
How can the law of Christ
permit a layman, even a king,

321
00:25:34,117 --> 00:25:37,203
to be head of the Church?
MAN: Mm-hm.

322
00:25:37,204 --> 00:25:39,121
Boy, a little for me.

323
00:25:39,122 --> 00:25:41,729
[BELL TOLLlNG]

324
00:25:45,170 --> 00:25:47,777
[PRAYlNG lN LATlN]

325
00:25:55,472 --> 00:25:58,079
MEN:
Amen.

326
00:25:59,309 --> 00:26:02,687
FlSHER:
I must ask you, Sir Thomas,

327
00:26:02,688 --> 00:26:06,732
if you still have a mind
to resign your office?

328
00:26:06,733 --> 00:26:11,237
After the vote, Your Grace,
I must confess I was sorely tempted.

329
00:26:11,238 --> 00:26:13,656
But, on reflection,

330
00:26:13,657 --> 00:26:16,325
I am content to stay
and fight for Christendom.

331
00:26:16,326 --> 00:26:19,327
Oh, this is excellent news.

332
00:26:19,663 --> 00:26:23,165
As, indeed, is the turning again
of the archbishop. Hmm.

333
00:26:23,166 --> 00:26:25,960
I thank God that his conscience
has finally driven him

334
00:26:25,961 --> 00:26:29,046
to condemn the king's nullity suit.

335
00:26:29,047 --> 00:26:32,550
And he has stated his intention
to oppose any legislation,

336
00:26:32,551 --> 00:26:35,338
[MEN COUGHlNG, GAGGlNG]

337
00:26:38,557 --> 00:26:41,350
which might be injurious
to the Church.

338
00:26:41,351 --> 00:26:44,436
[MEN GAGGlNG, GASPlNG]

339
00:26:47,649 --> 00:26:49,567
MORE:
Get a doctor.

340
00:26:49,568 --> 00:26:52,153
Fetch a doctor, quick.

341
00:26:52,154 --> 00:26:54,760
WOMAN:
Help, please help.

342
00:26:54,865 --> 00:26:57,472
God. God.

343
00:26:59,578 --> 00:27:02,121
MORE:
Four men died of their pains.

344
00:27:02,122 --> 00:27:03,330
[SCRlBBLlNG]

345
00:27:03,332 --> 00:27:07,960
Bishop Fisher survived only
because he ate so little of the soup.

346
00:27:07,961 --> 00:27:10,796
It's very unfortunate, Sir Thomas.

347
00:27:10,797 --> 00:27:14,300
It's more than unfortunate,
Your Majesty.

348
00:27:14,301 --> 00:27:15,551
[SlGHS]

349
00:27:15,552 --> 00:27:18,971
Now, Fisher's cook
has been arrested.

350
00:27:18,972 --> 00:27:21,579
But I must tell you that--

351
00:27:21,683 --> 00:27:28,586
That rumours abound
as to the identity of those
who plotted against him.

352
00:27:28,815 --> 00:27:32,149
Who?
Wiltshire has been named.

353
00:27:32,569 --> 00:27:35,176
Boleyn?
Yes.

354
00:27:35,280 --> 00:27:36,614
And...

355
00:27:36,615 --> 00:27:37,990
[BELL TOLLlNG, HENRY SlGHS]

356
00:27:37,991 --> 00:27:40,910
Ahem. Well, some people
even blame the Lady Anne.

357
00:27:40,911 --> 00:27:44,580
Oh, some people will blame her
for everything!

358
00:27:44,581 --> 00:27:48,000
They will blame her if it rains
or if the rains fail.

359
00:27:48,001 --> 00:27:51,587
They'll blame her for the
barrenness of the queen
and for the fact that I love her.

360
00:27:51,588 --> 00:27:54,381
They'll blame her for the wind that
destroys our crops,

361
00:27:54,383 --> 00:28:01,358
and the storms that sink our ships.
It's all the fault of the Lady Anne.

362
00:28:02,015 --> 00:28:04,622
[SlGHlNG]

363
00:28:07,229 --> 00:28:09,647
[BELL RlNGlNG lN DlSTANCE]

364
00:28:09,648 --> 00:28:12,024
What about you, Sir Thomas?

365
00:28:12,025 --> 00:28:14,527
Do you blame her?

366
00:28:14,528 --> 00:28:16,987
Do you think she tried to poison
Bishop Fisher?

367
00:28:16,988 --> 00:28:21,097
Harry, l--
Oh, the time for Harry is over.

368
00:28:22,077 --> 00:28:24,036
Well...

369
00:28:24,037 --> 00:28:26,539
Whoever was to blame,

370
00:28:26,540 --> 00:28:31,043
the cook, Roose, tried blatantly
and almost successfully,

371
00:28:31,044 --> 00:28:33,879
to poison one of Your Majesty's
great public servants,

372
00:28:33,880 --> 00:28:36,757
a bishop of our Holy Church,
as well as me.

373
00:28:36,758 --> 00:28:38,384
[SlGHS]

374
00:28:38,385 --> 00:28:41,220
If Your Majesty were to turn
a blind eye to the offence,

375
00:28:41,221 --> 00:28:46,308
everyone would be forced to assume
that the attempted murders

376
00:28:46,309 --> 00:28:48,853
were done with your blessing.

377
00:28:48,854 --> 00:28:51,460
[###]

378
00:28:55,527 --> 00:28:58,134
[SlGHS]

379
00:29:00,782 --> 00:29:03,389
[MEN YELLlNG]

380
00:29:08,373 --> 00:29:10,980
CROMWELL:
My Lord Boleyn.

381
00:29:17,549 --> 00:29:19,258
Mr. Roose,

382
00:29:19,259 --> 00:29:25,629
we've been going over and over
this all day, so one more time:

383
00:29:26,141 --> 00:29:28,748
Who gave you the poison?

384
00:29:32,439 --> 00:29:33,898
[SlGHS]

385
00:29:33,899 --> 00:29:37,443
Mr. Roose, it is inconceivable
that you should suddenly
take it upon yourself

386
00:29:37,444 --> 00:29:40,070
to murder your master
and his household,

387
00:29:40,071 --> 00:29:43,908
after serving him so diligently
these past four years.

388
00:29:43,909 --> 00:29:47,075
Who gave you the poison?

389
00:29:51,958 --> 00:29:54,628
Sir, I have three daughters.

390
00:30:01,802 --> 00:30:04,408
What is that to me?

391
00:30:09,684 --> 00:30:12,938
I want them to find good husbands.

392
00:30:13,396 --> 00:30:16,003
But that takes money.

393
00:30:20,278 --> 00:30:23,782
We can pay you
for your information.

394
00:30:24,616 --> 00:30:27,223
No, sir.

395
00:30:28,161 --> 00:30:30,866
The payment is already made,

396
00:30:31,665 --> 00:30:34,271
the account settled.

397
00:30:44,886 --> 00:30:47,096
You're a fool.

398
00:30:47,097 --> 00:30:49,704
And you will die for it.

399
00:30:50,976 --> 00:30:53,936
WOMAN: Hurry, come along.
MAN: Hold on, sir.

400
00:30:53,937 --> 00:30:56,021
[PEOPLE CHATTERlNG,
lNSTRUMENTAL MUSlC PLAYlNG]

401
00:30:56,022 --> 00:30:57,856
GROUP:
Lady Anne.

402
00:30:57,857 --> 00:30:59,692
MAN 1 : Lady Anne.
MAN 2: Lady Anne.

403
00:30:59,693 --> 00:31:02,299
MAN 3:
My lady.

404
00:31:05,532 --> 00:31:08,139
You. Hold a moment.

405
00:31:15,041 --> 00:31:16,959
Where are you taking this linen?

406
00:31:16,960 --> 00:31:19,744
To the Queen's Majesty.
Why?

407
00:31:19,796 --> 00:31:23,465
To make shirts for His Majesty.
She always has done.

408
00:31:23,466 --> 00:31:25,843
She still makes his shirts?

409
00:31:25,844 --> 00:31:28,451
Yes, Mistress Anne.

410
00:31:29,598 --> 00:31:32,204
[###]

411
00:31:50,327 --> 00:31:52,933
[SlGHS]

412
00:32:02,130 --> 00:32:04,715
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

413
00:32:04,716 --> 00:32:06,091
Sweetheart.

414
00:32:06,092 --> 00:32:07,885
How could you?

415
00:32:07,886 --> 00:32:09,511
What?
Your shirts.

416
00:32:09,512 --> 00:32:12,765
She still makes your shirts.
How could you let her?

417
00:32:12,766 --> 00:32:15,769
I hadn't even thought about it.

418
00:32:17,062 --> 00:32:20,356
You told me there was nothing
intimate between you anymore.

419
00:32:20,357 --> 00:32:23,692
There isn't. What's intimate?
They're just shirts, for God's sake.

420
00:32:23,693 --> 00:32:26,070
No, they're not just shirts.

421
00:32:26,071 --> 00:32:29,573
They are you and me.
They are you and her.

422
00:32:29,574 --> 00:32:31,075
I don't understand.

423
00:32:31,076 --> 00:32:33,452
Then you ought to.

424
00:32:33,453 --> 00:32:38,791
It's so hard,
when we're to be married,
but she's still here.

425
00:32:38,792 --> 00:32:41,627
You can't have three people
in a marriage.

426
00:32:41,628 --> 00:32:43,504
Why can't you see that?

427
00:32:43,505 --> 00:32:44,963
And why can't you understand

428
00:32:44,965 --> 00:32:50,261
that I have more things
to think about than my shirts?!

429
00:32:56,434 --> 00:33:00,938
MORE:
The king has agreed to a new
and harsh treatment of poisoners.

430
00:33:00,939 --> 00:33:03,556
They're to be boiled alive.

431
00:33:04,901 --> 00:33:09,238
He is wise to have dealt
so severely in this case.

432
00:33:09,239 --> 00:33:12,607
But he cannot avoid
some suspicion.

433
00:33:12,659 --> 00:33:16,632
At least against the Lady
and her father.

434
00:33:17,163 --> 00:33:20,864
We are all in the hands of God.

435
00:33:22,877 --> 00:33:27,872
But I worry that,
while I lie here uselessly,

436
00:33:28,341 --> 00:33:30,884
the king may proceed
with his divorce

437
00:33:30,885 --> 00:33:34,634
since he has given himself
the power.

438
00:33:34,848 --> 00:33:37,391
I was told that at the last council,

439
00:33:37,392 --> 00:33:39,643
the king became angry,

440
00:33:39,644 --> 00:33:41,812
and demanded
to know what would happen

441
00:33:41,813 --> 00:33:43,730
if he went ahead anyway
and married Anne

442
00:33:43,732 --> 00:33:45,607
without the pope's permission.

443
00:33:45,608 --> 00:33:48,444
And what did they say?

444
00:33:48,653 --> 00:33:53,846
Only Boleyn supported him.
Not even his friend Brandon.

445
00:33:54,367 --> 00:33:56,974
Thank God.

446
00:33:58,538 --> 00:34:00,038
[DOOR BANGS LOUDLY]

447
00:34:00,039 --> 00:34:03,136
HENRY: Catherine.
WOMAN: Majesty.

448
00:34:06,463 --> 00:34:08,380
Husband.

449
00:34:08,381 --> 00:34:10,757
How are you feeling?
What?

450
00:34:10,759 --> 00:34:14,720
They told me you have been
suffering from a toothache
which I know is a terrible pain.

451
00:34:14,721 --> 00:34:17,014
And someone even said
you had a touch of gout.

452
00:34:17,015 --> 00:34:18,474
Of course I don't have gout.

453
00:34:18,475 --> 00:34:22,102
I don't know why you even listen
to such stupid rumours.

454
00:34:22,103 --> 00:34:24,710
Because I care for you.

455
00:34:26,566 --> 00:34:31,695
Catherine, you're going to have
to stop making my shirts.

456
00:34:31,696 --> 00:34:33,947
I thought you liked the shirts
I made for you.

457
00:34:33,948 --> 00:34:36,555
I see you are wearing one.

458
00:34:38,244 --> 00:34:40,851
Henry--
What now?

459
00:34:42,040 --> 00:34:45,241
Our daughter Mary has been unwell.

460
00:34:45,502 --> 00:34:49,087
She has not kept any food down
for eight days now.

461
00:34:49,088 --> 00:34:51,465
Do you not think
we should visit her?

462
00:34:51,466 --> 00:34:54,301
You can go and visit the princess
if you like.

463
00:34:54,302 --> 00:34:56,909
And you can stay there.

464
00:34:58,807 --> 00:35:03,435
Henry, not for our daughter, nor for
anyone, would I dream of leaving you.

465
00:35:03,436 --> 00:35:04,645
[SCOFFS]

466
00:35:04,646 --> 00:35:07,898
You know my rightful place
is by your side.

467
00:35:07,899 --> 00:35:10,506
[###]

468
00:35:15,031 --> 00:35:17,638
[DOOR SLAMS]

469
00:35:20,286 --> 00:35:21,495
[LlQUlD BOlLlNG]

470
00:35:21,496 --> 00:35:25,302
ROOSE:
I consign myself to God's mercy.

471
00:35:25,792 --> 00:35:27,417
Bless you, sir.

472
00:35:27,418 --> 00:35:31,829
Tell my girls I died easily
and with no pain.

473
00:35:32,465 --> 00:35:34,299
Head first?

474
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:36,218
Or however it comes?

475
00:35:36,219 --> 00:35:38,826
[ROOSE PRAYlNG lN LATlN]

476
00:35:55,446 --> 00:35:58,053
[CRYlNG]

477
00:36:01,411 --> 00:36:04,018
ROOSE:
Save me.

478
00:36:06,166 --> 00:36:08,772
[GASPlNG]

479
00:36:14,465 --> 00:36:17,072
[SCREAMlNG]

480
00:36:34,152 --> 00:36:36,759
[DANCE MUSlC PLAYlNG]

481
00:36:37,405 --> 00:36:40,012
[PEOPLE CHATTERlNG]

482
00:37:08,519 --> 00:37:11,126
Sit.

483
00:37:16,277 --> 00:37:19,154
Your wife looks very beautiful.

484
00:37:19,155 --> 00:37:21,073
You seem very happy together.

485
00:37:21,074 --> 00:37:23,533
BRANDON:
Yes, we are.

486
00:37:23,534 --> 00:37:28,372
A happy marriage is devoutly
something to be wished for.

487
00:37:28,373 --> 00:37:33,210
Talking of which,
I want you to do something for me.

488
00:37:33,211 --> 00:37:35,818
[WHlSPERlNG]

489
00:37:51,813 --> 00:37:54,419
[DOOR CLOSES]

490
00:37:58,695 --> 00:38:01,565
Your Grace.
Madam.

491
00:38:02,365 --> 00:38:06,087
I need to speak to Your Majesty
alone.

492
00:38:13,960 --> 00:38:17,985
The king has sent you?
At this hour? Why?

493
00:38:18,631 --> 00:38:21,299
The king asks you to be sensible.

494
00:38:21,301 --> 00:38:24,511
Withdraw your appeal to Rome
and entrust your affairs to his hands.

495
00:38:24,512 --> 00:38:28,056
And he promises
to be more than generous.

496
00:38:28,057 --> 00:38:30,434
As you know, Parliament has now
voted to make him supreme

497
00:38:30,435 --> 00:38:32,978
in all matters spiritual
as well as temporal.

498
00:38:32,979 --> 00:38:34,563
No.

499
00:38:34,564 --> 00:38:37,190
Only the pope has God's power
here on Earth,

500
00:38:37,191 --> 00:38:39,609
and is the image of eternal truth.

501
00:38:39,610 --> 00:38:42,947
Yes, but the king is--
Your Grace.

502
00:38:43,656 --> 00:38:45,490
I love and have loved His Majesty

503
00:38:45,491 --> 00:38:48,326
as much as any woman
can love a man.

504
00:38:48,328 --> 00:38:50,996
But I would not have borne
him company as his wife

505
00:38:50,997 --> 00:38:55,167
one moment against the voice
of my conscience.

506
00:38:55,168 --> 00:38:58,584
I am his true wife.

507
00:39:00,965 --> 00:39:05,135
Go to Rome, if you want, and argue it
there with lots of important men

508
00:39:05,136 --> 00:39:09,109
